# Global Audit Memory

## Scope Touched
- Persistent core scope: `VirtualToken.sol`, `LamboFactory.sol`, `LamboVEthRouter.sol`, `rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol`; recurring secondary scope: `LamboToken.sol`, `Utils/LaunchPadUtils.sol`, with periodic Uniswap V2 library/interface dependency checks.
- Highest sustained attention remains on router/rebalance + virtual accounting boundaries, especially `LamboVEthRouter.sol`, `VirtualToken.sol`, and `rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol`.
- Factory launch/pool setup assumptions and Uniswap V2 pair/LP mechanics remain recurring structural dependencies.

## Issue Directions Seen
- Durable core direction: accounting-consistency gaps between virtual debt/mint-burn semantics and real backing/transferability assumptions.
- Durable boundary-control direction: router-level whitelist or redemption-intent boundaries can be weakened by composable pair routing (`quoteToken/vETH` pathing into `cashOut`).
- Durable execution direction: rebalance correctness is sensitive to swap-direction/token-order derivation and deployment-specific pool metadata assumptions.
- Durable liquidity-model direction: LP-burn finality assumptions are unstable under Uniswap V2 `feeTo` protocol-fee mint behavior.
- Durable launch-flow direction: init/pool-creation sequencing and deterministic-address assumptions can create launch fragility/DoS conditions.
- Durable funds-handling direction: native ETH can accumulate in router/rebalancer surfaces that accept ETH but lack explicit rescue flows.
- Secondary/unsettled direction: descriptor/mask composition in rebalance path remains a low-confidence, periodically resurfacing concern.

## Useful Context
- Highest-yield work continues to be end-to-end call-path validation across factory -> router -> rebalance -> virtual token accounting, rather than isolated checks.
- Cross-agent convergence is strongest at router/rebalance boundaries; most durable signals continue to come from adversarial testing of those interfaces.
- Many broad governance/slippage/accounting hypotheses recur, but retained issues usually hinge on concrete boundary violations or asset-recovery invariants.
